Chapter Nine

Ray Optics and Optical Instruments


9.1  Introduction
Nature has endowed the human eye (retina) with the sensitivity to detect electromagnetic waves within a small range of the electromagnetic spectrum.", "fibs": ["Chapter"]}
{"text": "Electromagnetic radiation belonging to this region of the spectrum (wavelength of about 400 nm to 750 nm) is called light.", "fibs": ["radiation"]}
{"text": "It is mainly through light and the sense of vision that we know and interpret the world around us.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "There are two things that we can intuitively mention about light from common experience.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "First, that it travels with enormous speed and second, that it travels in a straight line.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "It took some time for people to realise that the speed of light is finite and measurable.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "Its presently accepted value in vacuum is c = 2.99792458 × 108 m s–1.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "For many purposes, it suffices to take c = 3 × 108 m s–1.", "fibs": ["×"]}
{"text": "The speed of light in vacuum is the highest speed attainable in nature.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "The intuitive notion that light travels in a straight line seems to contradict what we have learnt in Chapter 8, that light is an electromagnetic wave of wavelength belonging to the visible part of the spectrum.", "fibs": ["notion"]}
{"text": "The answer is that the wavelength of light is very small compared to the size of ordinary objects that we encounter commonly (generally of the order of a few cm or larger).", "fibs": ["answer"]}
{"text": "In this situation, as you will learn in Chapter 10, a light wave can be considered to travel from one point to another, along a straight line joining them.", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "The path is called a ray of light, and a bundle of such rays constitutes a beam of light.", "fibs": ["path"]}
{"text": "In this chapter, we consider the phenomena of reflection, refraction and dispersion of light, using the ray picture of light.", "fibs": ["chapter"]}
{"text": "Using the basic laws of reflection and refraction, we shall study the image formation by plane and spherical reflecting and refracting surfaces.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "We then go on to describe the construction and working of some important optical instruments, including the human eye.", "fibs": ["construction"]}
{"text": "Particle model of light
Newton’s fundamental contributions to mathematics, mechanics, and gravitation often blind us to his deep experimental and theoretical study of light.", "fibs": ["Particle"]}
{"text": "He made pioneering contributions in the field of optics.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "He further developed the corpuscular model of light proposed by Descartes.", "fibs": ["model"]}
{"text": "It presumes that light energy is concentrated in tiny particles called corpuscles.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "He further assumed that corpuscles of light were massless elastic particles.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "With his understanding of mechanics, he could come up with a simple model of reflection and refraction.", "fibs": ["understanding"]}
{"text": "It is a common observation that a ball bouncing from a smooth plane surface obeys the laws of reflection.", "fibs": ["observation"]}
{"text": "When this is an elastic collision, the magnitude of the velocity remains the same.", "fibs": ["collision"]}
{"text": "As the surface is smooth, there is no force acting parallel to the surface, so the component of momentum in this direction also remains the same.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "Only the component perpendicular to the surface, i.e., the normal component of the momentum, gets reversed in reflection.", "fibs": ["component"]}
{"text": "Newton argued that smooth surfaces like mirrors reflect the corpuscles in a similar manner.", "fibs": ["manner"]}
{"text": "In order to explain the phenomena of refraction, Newton postulated that the speed of the corpuscles was greater in water or glass than in air.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "However, later on it was discovered that the speed of light is less in water or glass than in air.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "In the field of optics, Newton – the experimenter, was greater than Newton – the theorist.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "He himself observed many phenomena, which were difficult to understand in terms of particle nature of light.", "fibs": ["particle"]}
{"text": "For example, the colours observed due to a thin film of oil on water.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Property of partial reflection of light is yet another such example.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "Everyone who has looked into the water in a pond sees image of the face in it, but also sees the bottom of the pond.", "fibs": ["Everyone"]}
{"text": "Newton argued that some of the corpuscles, which fall on the water, get reflected and some get transmitted.", "fibs": ["fall"]}
{"text": "But what property could distinguish these two kinds of corpuscles?", "fibs": ["property"]}
{"text": "Newton had to postulate some kind of unpredictable, chance phenomenon, which decided whether an individual corpuscle would be reflected or not.", "fibs": ["kind"]}
{"text": "Such a dilemma does not occur in the wave picture of light.", "fibs": ["dilemma"]}
{"text": "An incoming wave can be divided into two weaker waves at the boundary between air and water.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "9.2  Reflection of Light by Spherical Mirrors
We are familiar with the laws of reflection.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "The angle of reflection (i.e., the angle between reflected ray and the normal to the reflecting surface or the mirror) equals the angle of incidence (angle between incident ray and the normal).", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "Also that the incident ray, reflected ray and the normal to the reflecting surface at the point of incidence lie in the same plane (Fig.", "fibs": ["incident"]}
{"text": "These laws are valid at each point on any reflecting surface whether plane or curved.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "However, we shall restrict our discussion to the special case of curved surfaces, that is, spherical surfaces.", "fibs": ["discussion"]}
{"text": "The normal in this case is to be taken as normal to the tangent to surface at the point of incidence.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "That is, the normal is along the radius, the line joining the centre of curvature of the mirror to the point of incidence.", "fibs": ["radius"]}
{"text": "Figure 9.1 The incident ray, reflected ray and the normal to the reflecting surface lie in the same plane.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "We have already studied that the geometric centre of a spherical mirror is called its pole while that of a spherical lens is called its optical centre.", "fibs": ["centre"]}
{"text": "The line joining the pole and the centre of curvature of the spherical mirror is known as the principal axis.", "fibs": ["line"]}
{"text": "In the case of spherical lenses, the principal axis is the line joining the optical centre with its principal focus as you will see later.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "9.2.1  Sign convention
To derive the relevant formulae for reflection by spherical mirrors and refraction by spherical lenses, we must first adopt a sign convention for measuring distances.", "fibs": ["convention"]}
{"text": "In this book, we shall follow the Cartesian sign convention.", "fibs": ["book"]}
{"text": "According to this convention, all distances are measured from the pole of the mirror or the optical centre of the lens.", "fibs": ["convention"]}
{"text": "The distances measured in the same direction as the incident light are taken as positive and those measured in the direction opposite to the direction of incident light are taken as negative (Fig.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "The heights measured upwards with respect to x-axis and normal to the principal axis (x-axis) of the mirror/lens are taken as positive (Fig.", "fibs": ["respect"]}
{"text": "Figure 9.2 The Cartesian Sign Convention.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "With a common accepted convention, it turns out that a single formula for spherical mirrors and a single formula for spherical lenses can handle all different cases.", "fibs": ["convention"]}
