{"text": "9.3  Refraction
When a beam of light encounters another transparent medium, a part of light gets reflected back into the first medium while the rest enters the other.", "fibs": ["beam"]}
{"text": "A ray of light represents a beam.", "fibs": ["ray"]}
{"text": "The direction of propagation of an obliquely incident (0°< i < 90°) ray of light that enters the other medium, changes at the interface of the two media.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "This phenomenon is called refraction of light.", "fibs": ["phenomenon"]}
{"text": "Snell experimentally obtained the following laws of refraction:
(i)	The incident ray, the refracted ray and the normal to the interface at the point of incidence, all lie in the same plane.", "fibs": ["refraction"]}
{"text": "(ii)	The ratio of the sine of the angle of incidence to the sine of angle of refraction is constant.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "Remember that the angles of incidence (i ) and refraction (r ) are the angles that the incident and  its refracted ray make with the normal, respectively.", "fibs": ["incidence"]}
{"text": "We have
