where n21 is a constant, called the refractive index of the second medium with respect to the first medium.", "fibs": ["n21"]}
{"text": "Equation (9.10) is the well-known Snell’s law of refraction.", "fibs": ["Equation"]}
{"text": "We note that n21 is a characteristic of the pair of media (and also depends on the wavelength of light), but is independent of the angle of incidence.", "fibs": ["note"]}
{"text": "Figure 9.8 Refraction and reflection of light.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "From Eq.", "fibs": ["Eq."]}
{"text": "(9.10), if n21 > 1, r < i, i.e., the refracted ray bends towards the normal.", "fibs": ["n21"]}
{"text": "In such a case medium 2 is said to be optically denser (or denser, in short) than medium 1.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, if n21 <1, r > i, the refracted ray bends away from the normal.", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "This is the case when incident ray in a denser medium refracts into a rarer medium.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Note: Optical density should not be confused with mass density, which is mass per unit volume.", "fibs": ["density"]}
{"text": "It is possible that mass density of an optically denser medium may be less than that of an optically rarer medium (optical density is the ratio of the speed of light in two media).", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "For example, turpentine and water.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Mass density of turpentine is less than that of water but its optical density is higher.", "fibs": ["density"]}
