{"text": "9.4  Total Internal Reflection
When light travels from an optically denser medium to a rarer medium at the interface, it is partly reflected back into the same medium and partly refracted to the second medium.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "This reflection is called the internal reflection.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "When a ray of light enters from a denser medium to a rarer medium, it bends away from the normal, for example, the ray AO1 B in Fig.", "fibs": ["ray"]}
{"text": "The incident ray AO1 is partially reflected (O1C) and partially transmitted (O1B) or refracted, the angle of refraction (r) being larger than the angle of incidence (i).", "fibs": ["incident"]}
{"text": "As the angle of incidence increases, so does the angle of refraction, till for the ray AO3, the angle of refraction is π/2.", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "The refracted ray is bent so much away from the normal that it grazes the surface at the interface between the two media.", "fibs": ["ray"]}
{"text": "This is shown by the ray AO3 D in Fig.", "fibs": ["ray"]}
{"text": "If the angle of incidence is increased still further (e.g., the ray AO4), refraction is not possible, and the incident ray is totally reflected.", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "This is called total internal reflection.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "When light gets reflected by a surface, normally some fraction of it gets transmitted.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "The reflected ray, therefore, is always less intense than the incident ray, howsoever smooth the reflecting surface may be.", "fibs": ["ray"]}
{"text": "In total internal reflection, on the other hand, no transmission of light takes place.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "The angle of incidence corresponding to an angle of refraction 90°, say ∠AO3N, is called the critical angle (ic ) for the given pair of media.", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "We see from Snell’s law [Eq.", "fibs": ["’"]}
