{"text": "A demonstration for total internal reflection
All optical phenomena can be demonstrated very easily with the use of a laser torch or pointer, which is easily available nowadays.", "fibs": ["demonstration"]}
{"text": "Take a glass beaker with clear water in it.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "Add a few drops of milk or any other suspension to water and stir so that water becomes a little turbid.", "fibs": ["milk"]}
{"text": "Take a laser pointer and shine its beam through the turbid water.", "fibs": ["laser"]}
{"text": "You will find that the path of the beam inside the water shines brightly.", "fibs": ["path"]}
{"text": "Shine the beam from below the beaker such that it strikes at the upper water surface at the other end.", "fibs": ["beam"]}
{"text": "Do you find that it undergoes partial reflection (which is seen as a spot on the table below) and partial refraction [which comes out in the air and is seen as a spot on the roof; Fig.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "9.13(a)]?", "fibs": ["9.13(a"]}
{"text": "Now direct the laser beam from one side of the beaker such that it strikes the upper surface of water more obliquely [Fig.", "fibs": ["laser"]}
{"text": "9.13(b)].", "fibs": ["9.13(b"]}
{"text": "Adjust the direction of laser beam until you find the angle for which the refraction above the water surface is totally absent and the beam is totally reflected back to water.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "This is total internal reflection at its simplest.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "Pour this water in a long test tube and shine the laser light from top, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "9.13(c).", "fibs": ["9.13(c"]}
{"text": "Adjust the direction of the laser beam such that it is totally internally reflected every time it strikes the walls of the tube.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "Take care not to look into the laser beam directly and not to point it at anybody’s face.", "fibs": ["care"]}
{"text": "9.4.1	Total internal reflection in nature and its technological applications
(i) Mirage: On hot summer days, the air near the ground becomes hotter than the air at higher levels.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "The refractive index of air increases with its density.", "fibs": ["index"]}
{"text": "Hotter air is less dense, and has smaller refractive index than the cooler air.", "fibs": ["air"]}
{"text": "If the air currents are small, that is, the air is still, the optical density at different layers of air increases with height.", "fibs": ["air"]}
{"text": "As a result, light from  a tall object such as a tree, passes through a medium whose refractive index decreases towards the ground.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "Thus, a ray of light from such an object successively bends away from the normal and undergoes total internal reflection, if the angle of incidence for the air near the ground exceeds the critical angle.", "fibs": ["ray"]}
{"text": "This is shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "9.14(b).", "fibs": ["9.14(b"]}
{"text": "To a distant observer, the light appears to be coming from somewhere below the ground.", "fibs": ["observer"]}
{"text": "The observer naturally assumes that light is being reflected from the ground, say, by a pool of water near the tall object.", "fibs": ["observer"]}
{"text": "Such inverted images of distant tall objects cause an optical illusion to the observer.", "fibs": ["cause"]}
{"text": "This phenomenon is called mirage.", "fibs": ["phenomenon"]}
{"text": "This type of mirage is especially common in hot deserts.", "fibs": ["type"]}
{"text": "Some of you might have noticed that while moving in a bus or a car during a hot summer day, a distant patch of road, especially on a highway, appears to be wet.", "fibs": ["bus"]}
{"text": "But, you do not find any evidence of wetness when you reach that spot.", "fibs": ["evidence"]}
{"text": "This is also due to mirage.", "fibs": ["mirage"]}
{"text": "Figure 9.13 Observing total internal reflection in water with a laser beam (refraction due to glass of beaker neglected being very thin).", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "(ii)	Diamond: Diamonds are known for their spectacular brilliance.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "Their brilliance is mainly due to the total internal reflection of light inside them.", "fibs": ["brilliance"]}
{"text": "The critical angle for diamond-air interface (≅ 24.4°) is very small, therefore once light enters a diamond, it is very likely to undergo total internal reflection inside it.", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "Diamonds found in nature rarely exhibit the brilliance for which they are known.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "It is the technical skill of a diamond cutter which makes diamonds to sparkle so brilliantly.", "fibs": ["skill"]}
{"text": "By cutting the diamond suitably, multiple total internal reflections can be made to occur.", "fibs": ["diamond"]}
{"text": "Figure 9.14 (a) A tree is seen by an observer at its place when the air above the ground is at uniform temperature, (b) When the layers of air close to the ground have varying temperature with hottest layers near the ground, light from a distant tree may undergo total internal reflection, and the apparent image of the tree may create an illusion to the observer that the tree is near a pool of water.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "Figure 9.15 Prisms designed to bend rays by 90° and 180° or to invert image without changing its size make use of total internal reflection.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "(iii)	Prism: Prisms designed to bend light by 90° or by 180° make use of total internal reflection [Fig.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "9.15(a) and (b)].", "fibs": ["9.15(a"]}
{"text": "Such a prism is also used to invert images without changing their size [Fig.", "fibs": ["prism"]}
{"text": "9.15(c)].", "fibs": ["9.15(c"]}
{"text": "In the first two cases, the critical angle ic for the material of the prism must be less than 45°.", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "We see from Table 9.1 that this is true for both crown glass and dense flint glass.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "(iv)	Optical fibres: Nowadays optical fibres are extensively used for transmitting audio and video signals through long distances.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "Optical fibres too make use of the phenomenon of total internal reflection.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "Optical fibres are fabricated with high quality composite glass/quartz fibres.", "fibs": ["quality"]}
{"text": "Each fibre consists of a core and cladding.", "fibs": ["fibre"]}
{"text": "The refractive index of the material of the core is higher than that of the cladding.", "fibs": ["index"]}
{"text": "When a signal in the form of light is directed at one end of the fibre at a suitable angle, it undergoes repeated total internal reflections along the length of the fibre and finally comes out at the other end (Fig.", "fibs": ["signal"]}
{"text": "Since light undergoes total internal reflection at each stage, there is no appreciable loss in the intensity of the light signal.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Optical fibres are fabricated such that light reflected at one side of inner surface strikes the other at an angle larger than the critical angle.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Even if the fibre is bent, light can easily travel along its length.", "fibs": ["fibre"]}
{"text": "Thus, an optical fibre can be used to act as an optical pipe.", "fibs": ["fibre"]}
{"text": "Figure 9.16 Light undergoes successive total internal reflections as it moves through an optical fibre.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "A bundle of optical fibres can be put to several uses.", "fibs": ["bundle"]}
{"text": "Optical fibres are extensively used for transmitting and receiving electrical signals which are converted to light by suitable transducers.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Obviously, optical fibres can also be used for transmission of optical signals.", "fibs": ["transmission"]}
{"text": "For example, these are used as a ‘light pipe’ to facilitate visual examination of internal organs like esophagus, stomach and intestines.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "You might have seen a commonly available decorative lamp with fine plastic fibres with their free ends forming a fountain like structure.", "fibs": ["lamp"]}
{"text": "The other end of the fibres is fixed over an electric lamp.", "fibs": ["end"]}
{"text": "When the lamp is switched on, the light travels from the bottom of each fibre and appears at the tip of its free end as a dot of light.", "fibs": ["lamp"]}
{"text": "The main requirement in fabricating optical fibres is that there should be very little absorption of light as it travels for long distances inside them.", "fibs": ["requirement"]}
{"text": "This has been achieved by purification and special preparation of materials such as quartz.", "fibs": ["purification"]}
{"text": "In silica glass fibres, it is possible to transmit more than 95% of the light over a fibre length of 1 km.", "fibs": ["silica"]}
{"text": "(Compare with what you expect for a block of ordinary window glass 1 km thick.)", "fibs": ["block"]}
{"text": "9.5	Refraction at Spherical Surfaces And By Lenses
We have so far considered refraction at a plane interface.", "fibs": ["refraction"]}
{"text": "We shall now consider refraction at a spherical interface between two transparent media.", "fibs": ["refraction"]}
{"text": "An infinitesimal part of a spherical surface can be regarded as planar and the same laws of refraction can be applied at every point on the surface.", "fibs": ["part"]}
{"text": "Just as for reflection by a spherical mirror, the normal at the point of incidence is perpendicular to the tangent plane to the spherical surface at that point and, therefore, passes through its centre of curvature.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "We first consider refraction by a single spherical surface and follow it by thin lenses.", "fibs": ["refraction"]}
{"text": "A thin lens is a transparent optical medium bounded by two surfaces; at least one of which should be spherical.", "fibs": ["lens"]}
{"text": "Applying the formula for image formation by a single spherical surface successively at the two surfaces of a lens, we shall obtain the lens maker’s formula and then the lens formula.", "fibs": ["formula"]}
