Light sources and photometry
It is known that a body above absolute zero temperature emits electromagnetic radiation.", "fibs": ["∠NOM"]}
{"text": "The wavelength region in which the body emits the radiation depends on its absolute temperature.", "fibs": ["wavelength"]}
{"text": "Radiation emitted by a hot body, for example, a tungsten filament lamp having temperature 2850 K are partly invisible and mostly in infrared (or heat) region.", "fibs": ["Radiation"]}
{"text": "As the temperature of the body increases radiation emitted by it is in visible region.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "The sun with temperature of about 5500 K emits radiation whose energy versus wavelength graph peaks approximately at 550 nm corresponding to green light and is almost in the middle of the visible region.", "fibs": ["sun"]}
{"text": "The energy versus wavelength distribution graph for a given body peaks at some wavelength, which is inversely proportional to the absolute temperature of that body.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "The measurement of light as perceived by human eye is called photometry.", "fibs": ["measurement"]}
{"text": "Photometry is measurement of a physiological phenomenon, being the stimulus of light as received by the human eye, transmitted by the optic nerves and analysed by the brain.", "fibs": ["measurement"]}
{"text": "The main physical quantities in photometry are (i) the luminous intensity of the source, (ii) the luminous flux or flow of light from the source, and (iii) illuminance of the surface.", "fibs": ["photometry"]}
{"text": "The SI unit of luminous intensity (I) is candela (cd).", "fibs": ["SI"]}
{"text": "The candela is the luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540 × 1012 Hz and that has a radiant intensity in that direction of 1/683 watt per steradian.", "fibs": ["candela"]}
{"text": "If a light source emits one candela of luminous intensity into a solid angle of one steradian, the total luminous flux emitted into that solid angle is one lumen (lm).", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "A standard 100 watt incadescent light bulb emits approximately 1700 lumens.", "fibs": ["watt"]}
{"text": "In photometry, the only parameter, which can be measured directly is illuminance.", "fibs": ["photometry"]}
{"text": "It is defined as luminous flux incident per unit area on a surface (lm/m2 or lux).", "fibs": ["flux"]}
{"text": "Most light meters measure this quantity.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "The illuminance E, produced by a source of luminous intensity I, is given by E = I/r2, where r is the normal distance of the surface from the source.", "fibs": ["illuminance"]}
{"text": "A quantity named luminance (L), is used to characterise the brightness of emitting or reflecting flat surfaces.", "fibs": ["quantity"]}
{"text": "Its unit is cd/m2 (sometimes called ‘nit’ in industry).", "fibs": ["unit"]}
{"text": "A good LCD computer monitor has a brightness of about 250 nits.", "fibs": ["LCD"]}
