{"text": "In subsequent discussions of optical instruments (microscope and telescope) we shall assume the image to be at infinity.", "fibs": ["microscope"]}
{"text": "A simple microscope has a limited maximum magnification (≤ 9) for realistic focal lengths.", "fibs": ["microscope"]}
{"text": "For much larger magnifications, one uses two lenses, one compounding the effect of the other.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "This is known as a compound microscope.", "fibs": ["compound"]}
{"text": "A schematic diagram of a compound microscope is shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["diagram"]}
{"text": "The lens nearest the object, called the objective, forms a real, inverted, magnified image of the object.", "fibs": ["lens"]}
{"text": "This serves as the object for the second lens, the eyepiece, which functions essentially like a simple microscope or magnifier, produces the final image, which is enlarged and virtual.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "The first inverted image is thus near (at or within) the focal plane of the eyepiece, at a distance appropriate for final image formation at infinity, or a little closer for image formation at the near point.", "fibs": ["image"]}
{"text": "Clearly, the final image is inverted with respect to the original object.", "fibs": ["image"]}
