{"text": "9.8.2 Telescope
The telescope is used to provide angular magnification of distant objects (Fig.", "fibs": ["telescope"]}
{"text": "It also has an objective and an eyepiece.", "fibs": ["objective"]}
{"text": "But here, the objective has a large focal length and a much larger aperture than the eyepiece.", "fibs": ["objective"]}
{"text": "Light from a distant object enters the objective and a real image is formed in the tube at its second focal point.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "The eyepiece magnifies this image producing a final inverted image.", "fibs": ["eyepiece"]}
{"text": "The magnifying power m is the ratio of the angle β subtended at the eye by the final image to the angle α which the object subtends at the lens or the eye.", "fibs": ["power"]}
{"text": "Hence
                (9.46)
In this case, the length of the telescope tube is fo + fe.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Terrestrial telescopes have, in addition, a pair of inverting lenses to make the final image erect.", "fibs": ["addition"]}
{"text": "For example, consider a telescope whose objective has a focal length of 100 cm and the eyepiece a focal length of 1 cm.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The magnifying power of this telescope is m = 100/1 = 100.", "fibs": ["power"]}
{"text": "Let us consider a pair of stars of actual separation 1′ (one minute of arc).", "fibs": ["pair"]}
{"text": "The stars appear as though they are separated by an angle of 100 × 1′ = 100′ =1.67°.", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "The main considerations with an astronomical telescope are its light gathering power and its resolution or resolving power.", "fibs": ["telescope"]}
{"text": "The former clearly depends on the area of the objective.", "fibs": ["area"]}
{"text": "The resolving power, or the ability to observe two objects distinctly, which are in very nearly the same direction, also depends on the diameter of the objective.", "fibs": ["power"]}
{"text": "So, the desirable aim in optical telescopes is to make them with objective of large diameter.", "fibs": ["aim"]}
{"text": "The largest lens objective in use has a diameter of 40 inch (~1.02 m).", "fibs": ["lens"]}
{"text": "Such big lenses tend to be very heavy and therefore, difficult to make and support by their edges.", "fibs": ["support"]}
{"text": "Further, it is rather difficult and expensive to make such large sized lenses which form images that are free from any kind of chromatic aberration and distortions.", "fibs": ["form"]}
{"text": "Figure 9.29 A refracting telescope.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "For these reasons, modern telescopes use a concave mirror rather than a lens for the objective.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "Telescopes with mirror objectives are called reflecting telescopes.", "fibs": ["mirror"]}
{"text": "There is no chromatic aberration in a mirror.", "fibs": ["aberration"]}
{"text": "Mechanical support is much less of a problem since a mirror weighs much less than a lens of equivalent optical quality, and can be supported over its entire back surface, not just over its rim.", "fibs": ["support"]}
{"text": "One obvious problem with a reflecting telescope is that the objective mirror focusses light inside the telescope tube.", "fibs": ["problem"]}
{"text": "One must have an eyepiece and the observer right there, obstructing some light (depending on the size of the observer cage).", "fibs": ["eyepiece"]}
{"text": "This is what is done in the very large 200 inch (~5.08 m) diameters, Mt.", "fibs": ["inch"]}
{"text": "Palomar telescope, California.", "fibs": ["telescope"]}
{"text": "The viewer sits near the focal point of the mirror, in a small cage.", "fibs": ["viewer"]}
{"text": "Another solution to the problem is to deflect the light being focussed by another mirror.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "One such arrangement using a convex secondary mirror to focus the incident light, which now passes through a hole in the objective primary mirror, is shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "This is known as a Cassegrain telescope, after its inventor.", "fibs": ["telescope"]}
{"text": "It has the advantages of a large focal length in a short telescope.", "fibs": ["length"]}
{"text": "The largest telescope in India is in Kavalur, Tamil Nadu.", "fibs": ["telescope"]}
{"text": "It is a 2.34 m diameter reflecting telescope (Cassegrain).", "fibs": ["diameter"]}
{"text": "It was ground, polished, set up, and is being used by the Indian Institute of Astrophysics, Bangalore.", "fibs": ["ground"]}
{"text": "The largest reflecting telescopes in the world are the pair of Keck telescopes in Hawaii, USA, with a reflector of 10 metre in diameter.", "fibs": ["world"]}
{"text": "Figure 9.30 Schematic diagram of a reflecting telescope (Cassegrain).", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "Reflection is governed by the equation ∠i = ∠r′  and refraction by the  Snell’s law, sini/sinr = n, where the incident ray, reflected ray, refracted ray and normal lie in the same plane.", "fibs": ["Reflection"]}
{"text": "Angles of incidence, reflection and refraction are i, r ′ and r, respectively.", "fibs": ["incidence"]}
{"text": "The critical angle of incidence ic for a ray incident from a denser to rarer medium, is that angle for which the angle of refraction is 90°.", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "For i > ic, total internal reflection occurs.", "fibs": ["ic"]}
{"text": "Multiple internal reflections in diamond (ic  ≅ 24.4°), totally reflecting prisms and mirage, are some examples of total internal reflection.", "fibs": ["diamond"]}
{"text": "Optical fibres consist of glass fibres coated with a thin layer of material of lower refractive index.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "Light incident at an angle at one end comes out at the other, after multiple internal reflections, even if the fibre is bent.", "fibs": ["incident"]}
