{"text": "The laws of reflection and refraction are true for all surfaces and pairs of media at the point of the incidence.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "The real image of an object placed between f and 2f from a convex lens can be seen on a screen placed at the image location.", "fibs": ["image"]}
{"text": "If the screen is removed, is the image still there?", "fibs": ["screen"]}
{"text": "This question puzzles many, because it is difficult to reconcile ourselves with an image suspended in air without a screen.", "fibs": ["question"]}
{"text": "But the image does exist.", "fibs": ["image"]}
{"text": "Rays from a given point on the object are converging to an image point in space and diverging away.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "The screen simply diffuses these rays, some of which reach our eye and we see the image.", "fibs": ["screen"]}
{"text": "This can be seen by the images formed in air during a laser show.", "fibs": ["air"]}
{"text": "Image formation needs regular reflection/refraction.", "fibs": ["Image"]}
{"text": "In principle, all rays from a given point should reach the same image point.", "fibs": ["principle"]}
{"text": "This is why you do not see your image by an irregular reflecting object, say the page of a book.", "fibs": ["image"]}
{"text": "Thick lenses give coloured images due to dispersion.", "fibs": ["dispersion"]}
{"text": "The variety in colour of objects we see around us is due to the constituent colours of the light incident on them.", "fibs": ["variety"]}
{"text": "A monochromatic light may produce an entirely different perception about the colours on an object as seen in white light.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "For a simple microscope, the angular size of the object equals the angular size of the image.", "fibs": ["microscope"]}
{"text": "Yet it offers magnification because we can keep the small object much closer to the eye than 25 cm and hence have it subtend a large angle.", "fibs": ["magnification"]}
{"text": "The image is at 25 cm which we can see.", "fibs": ["image"]}
{"text": "Without the microscope, you would need to keep the small object at 25 cm which would subtend a very small angle.", "fibs": ["microscope"]}
